<BaseLayout
  title="Med-Surgical 35 — Janet Owen"
  description="Unfolding case study: Acute Pancreatitis and Alcohol Withdrawal Management (MED-35)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/med-surgical/`}>Med-Surgical</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Med-Surgical 35 — Janet Owen</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">GI / Substance Use</span>
    <h1>Med-Surgical 35 — Janet Owen</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Acute Pancreatitis and Alcohol Withdrawal Management</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Janet Owen, 47 years, Caucasian Female</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>Handoff Report</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the oncoming nurse on the medical-surgical unit. You receive handoff for Janet Owen, a 47-year-old Caucasian female admitted for abdominal pain related to acute pancreatitis. She has a history of alcohol abuse disorder and alcoholic cirrhosis. She is currently NPO and in pain.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Janet Owen</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>47 years · Female · Caucasian</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Acute pancreatitis</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Secondary Dx</th><td>Alcohol abuse disorder; alcoholic cirrhosis of the liver</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admission reason</th><td>Severe abdominal pain</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Medications on MAR</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>½ Normal Saline + Multivitamins</strong> — IV (hydration + B-vitamin replacement)</li>
          <li><strong>Ondansetron (Zofran)</strong> — IV/PO (antiemetic)</li>
          <li><strong>Morphine sulfate</strong> — IV (pain management)</li>
          <li><strong>Lorazepam (Ativan)</strong> — IV/PO per CIWA-Ar protocol</li>
          <li><strong>Aluminum/Magnesium hydroxide (Maalox)</strong> — PO (antacid)</li>
          <li><strong>Famotidine (Pepcid)</strong> — PO/IV (H2 blocker)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Janet is lying in bed, curled slightly forward, appearing uncomfortable. She rates her abdominal pain as 8/10. She is NPO with an IV running. She appears anxious and says, "The pain just won't stop — it goes straight through to my back."</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why must thiamine be administered BEFORE glucose in alcoholic patients?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Wernicke's Encephalopathy Risk:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Chronic alcohol use depletes thiamine (Vitamin B1) stores</li>
          <li>Administering IV glucose without thiamine first triggers massive thiamine consumption for glucose metabolism</li>
          <li>Acute thiamine depletion can precipitate <strong>Wernicke's encephalopathy</strong>: confusion, ataxia, ophthalmoplegia (ocular paralysis)</li>
          <li>If untreated, Wernicke's progresses to <strong>Korsakoff's syndrome</strong> — irreversible amnesia</li>
          <li><strong>Clinical rule:</strong> Always administer thiamine BEFORE or concurrent with IV glucose in any patient with known or suspected chronic alcohol use</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Janet's ½NS with multivitamins provides thiamine replacement alongside IV hydration — this is intentional and protective.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ After handoff, you perform your initial assessment focused on the pancreatitis presentation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Pancreatitis Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You perform a focused assessment. Janet's vital signs show tachycardia and a low-grade fever. She describes severe epigastric pain that radiates to her back and worsens with eating. Abdominal assessment reveals diffuse tenderness, guarding, and absent bowel sounds.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩺 Assessment Findings</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Vital Signs</th><td>HR 108, Temp 38.2°C, BP 110/70, RR 18, SpO2 96%</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>8/10 epigastric; radiates to back; worsens with eating</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Abdomen</th><td>Diffuse tenderness; guarding; absent bowel sounds</td></tr>
            <tr><th>NPO status</th><td>Confirmed; no oral intake since admission</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Labs</th><td>Amylase elevated; lipase elevated; WBC elevated</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Hemorrhagic Pancreatitis Warning Signs</h3>
        <div class="callout callout-danger">
          <p><strong>Cullen's Sign</strong> — Periumbilical ecchymosis (bruising around navel)</p>
          <p><strong>Grey Turner's Sign</strong> — Flank ecchymosis (bruising along flanks)</p>
          <p>Either sign indicates retroperitoneal hemorrhage — a life-threatening complication of severe pancreatitis. <strong>Notify provider immediately</strong> if either sign is observed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is the pathophysiology of acute pancreatitis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Pancreatitis Pathophysiology:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Obstruction or injury</strong> — alcohol damages pancreatic acinar cells; causes premature activation of digestive enzymes within the pancreas (normally activated only in the duodenum)</li>
          <li><strong>Autodigestion</strong> — activated enzymes (trypsin, lipase, elastase) begin digesting pancreatic tissue itself</li>
          <li><strong>Inflammation</strong> — local inflammatory response triggers edema, hemorrhage, and necrosis</li>
          <li><strong>Systemic spillover</strong> — inflammatory mediators enter bloodstream → systemic effects (fever, tachycardia, third-spacing of fluids)</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Janet's dual pathology:</strong> Alcohol causes both pancreatitis (acinar cell damage) AND cirrhosis (hepatocyte damage) through different but related mechanisms.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With the assessment complete, you address Janet's pain and nausea…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Pain and Nausea Management</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Janet's pain is 8/10. She is also nauseated. You prepare to administer morphine IV and ondansetron IV per orders, and assist Janet to a comfortable position.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Pain Management Approach</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Morphine sulfate IV</strong> — administer per order; monitor RR and sedation; naloxone at bedside</li>
          <li><strong>Positioning</strong> — Semi-Fowler's or leaning forward reduces tension on inflamed pancreas; reduces pain</li>
          <li><strong>Reassess pain</strong> — 30–60 min post-administration; document response</li>
          <li><strong>Note on morphine:</strong> Older concern about sphincter of Oddi spasm — <em>current evidence supports morphine use</em> for pancreatitis pain</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🤢 Nausea Management</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Ondansetron (Zofran) IV</strong> — administer per order; assess bowel function</li>
          <li><strong>NPO maintenance</strong> — reinforce that nothing by mouth is required; explain rationale to Janet</li>
          <li><strong>IV fluids</strong> — ½NS with multivitamins running; ensure patency</li>
          <li><strong>Oral care</strong> — frequent mouth rinses to reduce discomfort from NPO status</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why is NPO status critical for acute pancreatitis management?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Why NPO is essential:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Eating stimulates the pancreas to secrete digestive enzymes</li>
          <li>In pancreatitis, those enzymes are already causing autodigestion — further stimulation worsens injury</li>
          <li><strong>Bowel rest = pancreatic rest</strong> — NPO allows the inflamed pancreas to "quiet down"</li>
          <li>Reduces nausea and vomiting (which are also triggered by eating)</li>
          <li>Prevents further enzyme activation and reduces pain</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Duration:</strong> NPO until pain is controlled and bowel function returns (usually 24–48 hours for mild pancreatitis). Nutritional support via enteral feeds (jejunal) if NPO is prolonged.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Several hours into your shift, you reassess Janet and begin CIWA-Ar monitoring…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Alcohol Withdrawal Recognition</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Janet has not consumed alcohol since before admission. As a heavy alcohol user, she is at risk for withdrawal syndrome as her blood alcohol level decreases. You perform a CIWA-Ar assessment.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 CIWA-Ar Assessment Tool (10 Items)</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Score Range</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Nausea / vomiting</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tremor</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Paroxysmal sweats</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Anxiety</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Agitation</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tactile disturbances</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Auditory disturbances</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Visual disturbances</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Headache / fullness in head</td><td>0–7</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Orientation / clouding of sensorium</td><td>0–4</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📈 CIWA-Ar Score Interpretation</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Score</th><th>Severity</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>&lt; 8</td><td>Mild</td><td>Monitor closely; may not need medication</td></tr>
            <tr><td>8–14</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Administer lorazepam per protocol</td></tr>
            <tr><td>≥ 15</td><td>Severe</td><td>Aggressive lorazepam; seizure precautions; notify provider</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-warning" style="margin-top:1rem;">
          <strong>⏱ Withdrawal Timeline After Last Drink</strong>
          <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
            <thead><tr><th>Time</th><th>Symptoms</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>6–24 hr</td><td>Anxiety, tremors, diaphoresis, tachycardia (mild)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>12–48 hr</td><td>Hallucinations (patient may know they are not real)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>24–48 hr</td><td>Seizures — peak risk period</td></tr>
              <tr><td>48–72 hr</td><td>Delirium tremens (DTs) — life-threatening</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>🛡️ Seizure Precautions — Implement for All Patients in Alcohol Withdrawal</strong>
      <p>Padded side rails · Suction at bedside · Oral airway available · Oxygen ready · Call light within reach · Bed in lowest position</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is the mortality risk of untreated delirium tremens (DTs)?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Delirium Tremens (DTs):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Most severe form of alcohol withdrawal; occurs 48–72 hours after last drink</li>
          <li>Characterized by: severe agitation, confusion, hallucinations (visual most common), fever, diaphoresis, severe autonomic instability (tachycardia, hypertension)</li>
          <li><strong>Mortality rate: 5–15% if untreated</strong></li>
          <li>With appropriate treatment (benzodiazepines, supportive care), mortality drops to &lt; 1%</li>
          <li>Janet's cirrhosis further increases her risk — liver disease impairs lorazepam metabolism; monitor carefully</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ An urgent change — Janet removes her IV line…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Alcohol Withdrawal Emergency — Patient Removes IV</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You enter Janet's room to find that she has pulled out her IV. She appears agitated, diaphoretic, and is looking around the room with fear. Her CIWA-Ar score is now ≥ 15, indicating severe withdrawal. She is trembling and says, "Get them off me — they're everywhere!"</p>
    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>🚨 Immediate Priorities</strong>
      <p>1. SAFETY — do not restrain without an order and exhausting alternatives first. 2. Calmly reorient Janet. 3. Score CIWA-Ar immediately. 4. Apply SWIPE seizure precautions. 5. Reestablish IV access. 6. Administer lorazepam per protocol.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🛡️ SWIPE Seizure Precautions</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>S</th><td>Siderails padded and up</td></tr>
            <tr><th>W</th><td>Wristband — verify identity</td></tr>
            <tr><th>I</th><td>IV — patient removed it; reestablish IV access</td></tr>
            <tr><th>P</th><td>Pull cord / call light within reach</td></tr>
            <tr><th>E</th><td>Equipment: suction, oral airway, O2 at bedside</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🗣️ Therapeutic Communication</h3>
        <div class="scene-box" style="margin-bottom:0;">
          <p><strong>Non-judgmental approach — avoid:</strong> "That's what happens when you drink too much."</p>
          <p><strong>Use instead:</strong> "Janet, I'm your nurse. You're safe. Your body has gotten used to alcohol and is reacting to not having it. We have medicine to help you through this safely."</p>
          <p>Speak calmly · Dim lights · Reduce stimulation · Do not argue with hallucinations · Validate that you understand she is frightened</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How does lorazepam work to treat alcohol withdrawal?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Mechanism of Lorazepam in Alcohol Withdrawal:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Alcohol acts as a GABA-A receptor agonist (enhances inhibitory neurotransmission) and suppresses NMDA glutamate activity (excitatory)</li>
          <li>With chronic alcohol use, the brain upregulates excitatory receptors and downregulates GABA receptors to compensate</li>
          <li>When alcohol is suddenly removed, this compensatory upregulation is now unopposed → CNS hyperexcitability → withdrawal symptoms and seizures</li>
          <li><strong>Lorazepam enhances GABA-A receptor activity</strong> → increases CNS inhibitory tone → reduces withdrawal severity and prevents seizures</li>
          <li><strong>Caution in Janet:</strong> Cirrhosis impairs hepatic metabolism of lorazepam → longer half-life → increased risk of respiratory depression. Monitor RR closely.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You stabilize Janet and complete your documentation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Nursing Diagnoses + SBAR</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Acute Pain</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: epigastric pain radiating to back, rated 8/10; guarding; elevated amylase and lipase</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Alcohol Withdrawal Syndrome</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: history of chronic alcohol abuse disorder; abrupt cessation at admission; CIWA-Ar monitoring initiated</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Imbalanced Nutrition: Less Than Body Requirements</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: NPO status; chronic alcohol use depleting B vitamins; nausea present</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Injury (Seizures)</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: alcohol withdrawal progression risk; CIWA-Ar score ≥ 15; seizure precautions implemented</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Ineffective Denial</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: history of alcohol abuse disorder; may minimize substance use problem; addiction counseling referral needed</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Janet's Alcohol Withdrawal Emergency</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>I am calling about Janet Owen, a 47-year-old female admitted with acute pancreatitis and alcohol abuse disorder. She has pulled out her IV and is showing signs of severe alcohol withdrawal — current CIWA-Ar score is 17.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Admitted for acute pancreatitis secondary to alcohol use. History of alcoholic cirrhosis. She has been NPO on ½NS with multivitamins, morphine for pain, and ondansetron for nausea. Her last drink was prior to admission approximately 24 hours ago. CIWA-Ar has been monitored since admission.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>She is severely agitated, diaphoretic, and reporting visual hallucinations ("they're everywhere"). CIWA-Ar score 17 — severe. She currently has no IV access. I have placed seizure precautions (padded rails, suction, oral airway, O2) and reoriented her. I am concerned for imminent seizure activity.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: order for lorazepam per CIWA-Ar protocol once IV is reestablished; order to restart IV fluids; social work and addiction counseling consultation. Should I obtain a STAT 12-lead ECG given autonomic instability? Please advise.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Morphine sulfate IV</strong></td>
          <td>Opioid analgesic (Schedule II)</td>
          <td>Monitor RR and sedation; naloxone at bedside; current evidence supports use in pancreatitis (older concern about sphincter of Oddi spasm is not evidence-based); assess pain 30–60 min post-dose</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Lorazepam (Ativan)</strong> <span class="badge-warning">HOLD criteria</span></td>
          <td>Benzodiazepine (Schedule IV)</td>
          <td><strong>HOLD if RR &lt; 10 or excessive sedation.</strong> Antidote: Flumazenil (Romazicon). Onset IV: 20–30 min. Hepatic metabolism — caution in Janet with cirrhosis (longer half-life). Dose guided by CIWA-Ar score. Monitor for respiratory depression.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ondansetron (Zofran)</strong></td>
          <td>5-HT3 serotonin receptor antagonist</td>
          <td>For nausea/vomiting from pancreatitis and opioid use; assess bowel function; monitor for QT prolongation at high doses</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>½NS + Multivitamins (thiamine)</strong></td>
          <td>IV fluid + B-vitamin replacement</td>
          <td>Thiamine (B1) must be replaced before or with glucose in alcoholic patients — prevents Wernicke's encephalopathy. Chronic alcohol depletes all B vitamins. Ensure IV patent and infusing correctly.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Famotidine (Pepcid)</strong></td>
          <td>H2-receptor antagonist</td>
          <td>Reduces gastric acid secretion; GI protection during acute illness and NPO status</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What are the signs and symptoms of acute pancreatitis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Classic presentation:</strong> Severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, worsened by eating, improved slightly by leaning forward; nausea and vomiting (vomiting does NOT relieve pain); diffuse abdominal tenderness with guarding; absent or hypoactive bowel sounds; low-grade fever; tachycardia.</p>
        <p><strong>Severe/hemorrhagic signs:</strong> Cullen's sign (periumbilical ecchymosis) and Grey Turner's sign (flank ecchymosis) indicate retroperitoneal hemorrhage — emergency.</p>
        <p><strong>Labs:</strong> Elevated amylase (>3× ULN) and lipase (more specific); elevated WBC; hyperglycemia; hypocalcemia.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: What are the clinical manifestations of pancreatitis (acute vs. chronic)?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Acute pancreatitis:</strong> Sudden onset severe abdominal pain, nausea/vomiting, fever, elevated amylase/lipase. Pain is the dominant symptom.</p>
        <p><strong>Chronic pancreatitis:</strong> Recurrent episodes of mild-to-moderate pain (often after eating or alcohol); steatorrhea (fatty stools from enzyme deficiency); weight loss; diabetes mellitus (beta cell destruction); malnutrition.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What is alcoholic cirrhosis and how is it related to pancreatitis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Chronic alcohol use causes both diseases through different mechanisms. Cirrhosis results from direct hepatocyte damage → inflammation → fibrosis → portal hypertension, coagulopathy, impaired drug metabolism. Pancreatitis results from alcohol increasing viscous pancreatic secretions and causing premature enzyme activation → autodigestion.</p>
        <p>Coexistence of both conditions is serious: impaired liver function affects drug metabolism (especially lorazepam — monitor carefully in Janet), coagulation, and nutritional status.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What is the focus of care for patients with pancreatitis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li>Pain management — adequate analgesia; assess frequently</li>
          <li>NPO / bowel rest — allows pancreas to rest and recover</li>
          <li>Aggressive IV fluid resuscitation — third-spacing causes significant losses</li>
          <li>Monitoring for complications: ARDS, AKI, hemorrhage, hyperglycemia, hypocalcemia</li>
          <li>Nutritional support — enteral (jejunal) if prolonged NPO</li>
          <li>Treat underlying cause — alcohol withdrawal prevention and management</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What is the CIWA-Ar tool and how is it used?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>CIWA-Ar (Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol, Revised) is a validated 10-item scale assessing alcohol withdrawal severity. Items include nausea, tremor, sweats, anxiety, agitation, tactile/auditory/visual disturbances, headache, and orientation. Each item scored 0–7 (orientation 0–4).</p>
        <p>Assessed every 1–4 hours per protocol. Score ≥ 8–10 typically triggers lorazepam administration. Score ≥ 15 = severe withdrawal requiring aggressive intervention. Continue monitoring until score &lt; 8 for 24 hours.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q6: What is the alcohol withdrawal timeline?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Time After Last Drink</th><th>Symptoms</th><th>Severity</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>6–24 hours</td><td>Anxiety, tremors, insomnia, tachycardia, diaphoresis, hypertension</td><td>Mild</td></tr>
            <tr><td>12–48 hours</td><td>Hallucinations (visual, auditory, tactile); patient may know they are not real</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
            <tr><td>24–48 hours</td><td>Seizures (generalized tonic-clonic) — peak risk</td><td>Severe</td></tr>
            <tr><td>48–72 hours</td><td>Delirium tremens (DTs) — agitation, confusion, hallucinations, fever, severe autonomic instability</td><td>Life-threatening (5–15% mortality if untreated)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

